# Naming and TypeScript Strictness

## Filenames – Always Kebab-Case

- All source files in this project should use **kebab-case** filenames:
  - ✅ `game-list.component.ts`
  - ✅ `team-details.service.ts`
  - ✅ `app-routing.module.ts`
  - ❌ `GameList.ts`, `gameList.ts`, `game_list.ts`
- Apply kebab-case consistently across backend (`backend/`) and frontend (`frontend/`) code, including:
  - Components, services, modules, controllers, DTOs, and utilities.

> When proposing or creating new files, always choose kebab-case names.

## TypeScript – Never Use any

- Do **not** use the `any` type in TypeScript code:
  - ❌ `let data: any;`
  - ❌ `function handle(input: any) { ... }`
- Prefer more precise alternatives:
  - Use concrete interfaces, types, or generics.
  - Use `unknown` when you truly do not know the shape and must narrow it.
  - Use union types or generics instead of falling back to `any`.

### Examples

```typescript
// ❌ BAD
function parseResponse(response: any): any {
  return response.data;
}

// ✅ GOOD
interface ApiResponse<T> {
  data: T;
}

function parseResponse<T>(response: ApiResponse<T>): T {
  return response.data;
}
```

The agent should **avoid generating or suggesting `any`** and, when refactoring, should opportunistically replace existing `any` usages with safer, well-typed alternatives.

